In the Penal Code of the State of New York, loitering falls under the category of crimes against public order, along with riots and illegal gathering[1]. Loitering by country
The conditions under which the police can detain loitering people vary. Sometimes the issue is intertwined with racial profiling. Canada
In Canada, the Supreme Court denied an appeal by a man who had a criminal record against a child and was arrested near a playground (en: R. v. Heywood). USA
In some places, loitering is a crime in itself, in others it is legal as long as the loitering has not committed another violation of the public order (searching for clients by prostitutes, begging, public consumption of alcoholic beverages).